==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gist
<hw>Gist</hw> <pr>(j⟦icr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>giste</ets> abode, lodgings, F. <ets>g⟦icir⟧te</ets>, fr.
<ets>g⟦eacute⟧sir</ets> to lie, L. <ets>jac⟦emac⟧re</ets>, prop., to be
thrown, hence, to lie, fr. <ets>jac⟦ecr⟧re</ets> to throw. In the second
sense fr. OF. <ets>gist</ets>, F. <ets>g⟦icir⟧t</ets>, 3d pers. sing.
ind. of <ets>g⟦eacute⟧sir</ets> to lie, used in a proverb, F., c'est
l⟦agrave⟧ que <ets>g⟦icir⟧t</ets> le li⟦egrave⟧vre, it is there that the
hare lies, <it>i. e.</it>, that is the point, the difficulty. See
<er>Jet</er> a shooting forth, and cf. <er>Agist</er>, <er>Joist</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Gest</er> a stage in traveling.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A resting place.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These quails have their set <qex>gists</qex>; to wit, ordinary
resting and baiting places.</q> <rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The main point, as of a question; the point on which
an action rests; the pith of a matter; <as>as, the <ex>gist</ex> of a
question</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Git</ent>⟦br⟧
